was, for the greater part of the time, entirely without the circle of the Roman Empire. It appears to me that such a change or transla- tion is not to be presumed, except it be proved by certain documents. I therefore hold that the Roman people is still the same people as formerly, before it received the admixture of strangers3 and that the Roman Empire rcmained in it, as in the body in which it existed and lived. For what the Roman people had formerly a right to do, before the Emperors reigned, it had the right of doing the same, when one Emperor was dead, and another not yet created. And even the election of the Emperor belonged to the people; and was sometimes made by the people, by itself, or by the Senate. And the elections which were made by the Legions, sometimes by one and sometimes by another, were not valid by any rights which the Legions had3 (for in so vague a name there could be no certain right3) but through the approbation of the people.
